  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each of the following functions, prove or
        disprove that the function is (i) a homomorphism; (ii)
        an isomorphism. (Remember to work with the default operation on each of these groups!)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>f:\Z\to\Z</m> defined by <m>f(n)=2n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>g:\R\to\R</m> defined by <m>g(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The function <m>h:\Q^*\to\Q^*</m> defined by
              <m>h(x)=x^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

  <solution>
    
    <ol>
    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>f</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>a,b \in
            \Z,</m> we have
            <me>
              f(a+b)=2(a+b)=2a+2b=f(a)+f(b).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>f</m> isn't a bijection, since it isn't onto: for instance, there is
            no element <m>a</m> in <m>\Z</m> such that <m>f(a)=3</m>. Thus, <m>f</m> is not an
            isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>g</m> isn't a homomorphism: for instance, we have
            <me>
              g(2+3)=g(5)=25\neq 13=4+9=g(2)+g(3).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Since it isn't a homomorphism, it isn't an isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>h</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>a,b \in
            \Q,</m> we have
            <me>
              h(ab)=(ab)^2=a^2b^2=h(a)h(b).
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The function <m>h</m> isn't onto: its range is the set of nonnegative rational
            numbers, not all of <m>\Q</m>. Thus, <m>h</m> is not an isomorphism.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
    </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Define <m>d : GL(n,\R)\to \R^*</m> by <m>d(A)=\det A</m>. Prove/disprove that <m>d</m> is:
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              a homomorphism
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              1-1
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              onto
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              an isomorphism.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

  <solution>
    
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          The function <m>d</m> is a homomorphism, since for every <m>A,B \in
          GL(n,\R),</m> we have
          <me>
            d(AB)=\det(AB)=(\det A)(\det B)=d(A)d(B).
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>d</m> isn't 1-1: For instance, <m>d(I_2)=d(-I_2)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>d</m> is onto: Let <m>a\in \R^*</m>. Then the matrix
          <me>
            A:=\begin{bmatrix}a \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  \cdots \amp  0 \\
            \vdots \amp  \vdots \amp  \vdots \amp  \ddots \amp  \vdots \\
            0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  \cdots \amp  1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          is in <m>GL(n,\R)</m>, with <m>d(A)=a</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Since <m>d</m> isn't 1-1, it isn't  an
          isomorphism.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

