  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>n\in \Z^+</m>. Prove that <m>\langle n\Z,+\rangle  \simeq \langle \Z,+\rangle</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  
  <solution>
    
    <p>
      Define <m>\phi\,:\,\Z \rightarrow n\Z</m>
      by <m>\phi(x)=nx</m>, for all <m>x\in \Z</m>. Clearly, <m>\phi</m>
      is a bijection. Moreover, for all <m>x,y\in \Z</m>,
      <me>
        \phi(x+y)=n(x+y)=nx+ny=\phi(x)+\phi(y);
      </me>
      so <m>\phi</m> is a
      homomorphism. Thus, <m>\phi</m> is an isomorphism, and hence
      <me>
        \langle \Z, +\rangle \simeq \langle n\Z, +\rangle .
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Let <m>G</m> and <m>G'</m> be groups, where <m>G</m> is abelian and  <m>G\simeq G'</m>. Prove that <m>G'</m> is abelian.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Give an example of groups <m>G</m> and <m>G'</m>, where <m>G</m> is abelian and there exists a homomorphism from <m>G</m> to <m>G'</m>, but <m>G'</m> is NOT abelian.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>

  <solution>
    
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Since <m>G\simeq G'</m>, there exists some isomorphism <m>\phi:G\to G'</m>.  Let <m>x,y\in G'</m>.  Since <m>\phi</m> is onto, there exist <m>a,b\in G</m> such that <m>\phi(a)=x</m> and <m>\phi(b)=y</m>.  So
          <md>
            <mrow>xy\amp =\phi(a)\phi(b)\amp \amp</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(ab)\amp \amp \text{ (since \(\phi\) is a homomorphism) }</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(ba) \amp \amp \text{ (since \(G\) is abelian) }</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =\phi(b)\phi(a)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =yx.</mrow>
          </md>
          Thus, <m>G'</m> is abelian.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Let <m>G=\{I_2\}</m> (under multiplication) and let <m>G'=GL(2,\R)</m>. Then the map <m>\phi: G\to G'</m> defined by <m>\phi(I_2)=I_2</m> is clearly a homomorphism, but note that <m>G</m> is abelian while <m>G'</m> is not.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
    </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\langle G,\cdot\rangle</m> and <m>\langle G',\cdot'\rangle</m> be groups with identity elements <m>e</m> and <m>e'</m>, respectively, and let <m>\phi</m> be a homomorphism from <m>G</m> to <m>G'</m>. Let <m>a\in G</m>. Prove that <m>\phi(a)^{-1}=\phi(a^{-1})</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

  <solution>
    
    <note>

    <p>
      We omit the group operations in this solution in order to increase familiarity with the convention.
    </p>

    </note>

    <p>
      We want to show that <m>\phi(a)^{-1}=\phi(a^{-1})</m>.
      Notice that
      <md>
        <mrow>\phi(a^{-1})\phi(a)\amp =\phi(a^{-1}a)\amp \amp \text{ (since \(\phi\) is a homomorphism) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\phi(e)\amp \amp \text{(by definition of \(a^{-1}\))}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =e'\amp \amp  \text{ (since \(\phi(e)\) is the identity element of
        \(G'\)) }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\phi(a)^{-1}\phi(a)\amp \amp \text{(by definition of \(\phi(a)^{-1}\))} .</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Thus, <m>\phi(a^{-1})=\phi(a)^{-1}</m>, by right cancellation.
    </p>
  </solution>
    </exercise>
